data.content:
**Root cause: C# 14 first-class span overload resolution change.**

In C# 14, implicit span conversions now fully participate in overload resolution. `array.Contains(x)` resolves to `MemoryExtensions.Contains<T>(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` (which wins due to its `IEquatable<T>` constraint) instead of the old `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)`.

`ReadOnlySpan<T>` is a **ref struct** — it cannot appear in expression trees. The expression tree compiler/interpreter chokes on this.

**Fix** — disambiguate by explicitly calling `Enumerable.Contains`:

```csharp
// Option 1: static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);

// Option 2: cast away the span conversion
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);
```

Both forms force the compiler back to the `IEnumerable<T>` overload, which expression trees support.
